A meteorologist with the National Weather Service told SFGATE there has been so much snow they are at "the point where it's getting hard to measure." 

A snow survey from the Natural Resources Conservation Service of California found the Lake Tahoe Basin snowpack was 219 percent of normal as of Feb. 21.

Full article and photos: http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Photos-show-the-insane-amounts-of-snow-piled-up-10950893.php

It's 129 feet high, and with subliminal flows from lava tubes at the middle of the wall, features both free falls over the brink as well as curtain-type falls that emerge from the wall itself.

#ThrowbackThursday: These days, the 'Firefall' at Yosemite National Park is something that only appears a couple weeks in February. It's a natural occurrence created by the angle of the setting sun. 

But that's a far cry from the original 'Firefall' tradition, which began in 1872 when camp workers would dump hot embers off the top of Glacier Point to the valley below. 

Check out this footage of the event from 1950, 18 years before the National Park Service put an end to the tradition because crowds grew too large.

Read more: http://bit.ly/2l9lqLq
link_name: TBT - The original Yosemite 'Firefall' - 1950 (via Getty)

status_message:
Ben and Rhonda met on a blind date in 1980. Ben didn't know this before the date but Rhonda was actually blind—had never seen a day in her life. 

They hit it off and ended up marrying just a few years later. Twenty years later Ben is diagnosed with a degenerative eye disease and over the course of just a few months becomes completely blind. 

Rhonda shows him how to do the little things—the every day actions that can keep a person alive, motivated and able to keep going after such a devastating loss.
link_name: Love Is Blind

On Saturday, the Marin Humane Society took in a dog surrendered by its owner. They soon discovered the scared, shivering dog had recently had puppies — puppies who were much too young to be separated from mom.

After some convincing, the owner surrendered the puppies too. When mom and puppies were reunited, the adorable interaction was captured on video. 

The great news: Momma dog Cora is back to being a happy, friendly dog and her puppies are in great health too. For more on this sweet family, check out our full story: http://bit.ly/1p922P0

Amid the unbridled joy of her players and assistant coaches celebrating their improbable WCC tournament championship Tuesday, USF head coach Jennifer Azzi understandably was both proud and stunned.

"I'm still a little bit in shock," Azzi said. "It's an overwhelming feeling."

The sixth-seeded Dons seemed overwhelmed at the start of Tuesday's game. Top-seeded BYU scored the first 10 points and led by 15 late in the first quarter.

But, led by seniors Taylor Proctor and Zhané Dikes, the Dons persevered. USF pulled out a 70-68 stunner to earn its first berth in the NCAA Tournament since 1997.

For the full story, click here: http://bit.ly/24PuXYZ
link_name: USF women stun BYU in WCC tournament final

An Altamont Corridor Express train that derailed Monday evening northeast of Fremont, sending nine people to local hospitals, left the tracks because of a mudslide near the rails.

All service on the line, which runs between San Jose and Stockton and carries 5,000 to 6,000 passengers a day, was halted Tuesday and workers from Union Pacific, the company that owns the tracks, were on the scene with heavy equipment and large cranes to pull the submerged car from Alameda Creek.

status_message:
Behold, the flowers of Death Valley. 

For the first time in over a decade, Death Valley National Park is experiencing a "super bloom," when millions of wildflowers blanket the barren desert. 

Every spring, some wildflowers bloom before it gets scorching hot, but the abundance of flowers this year is extremely unusual and happens about once every 10 years.

The last time there was a bloom of this magnitude was in 2005, and the time before that was in 1998.

For the full story, and more photos, click here: http://bit.ly/1M1RjuR
link_name: Field of yellow flowers in Death Valley, California (Footage v...

status_message:
A rare "super bloom" of wildflowers in Death Valley National Park has covered the hottest and driest place in North America with a carpet of gold. 

Unfortunately, the show won't last forever. Most of the flowers will wither in the next few weeks as temperatures start to rise.

Have you been? Share your pictures in the comments below!

For more on the super bloom, click here: http://bit.ly/1M1RjuR

status_message:
These days, a 'Firefall' at Yosemite National Park is something that only appears a couple weeks in February during sunset when there is abundant water flow down the mountain and clear skies.

This is a natural occurrence created by the angle of the setting sun, which seems to ignite the tumbling water. 

But it's a far cry from the original 'Firefall' tradition, which began in 1872 when camp workers would dump glowing hot embers from the top of Glacier Point to the valley approximately 3,000 feet below. 

Check out this footage of the event from 1950, 18 years before the National Park Service put an end to the tradition because crowds grew too large.

Read more about the 'Firefall' here: http://sfg.ly/1T86kTV
link_name: The original 'Firefall' tradition in Yosemite National Park, 1950

The Rim Fire, now the largest fire in recorded Sierra Nevada history, is rich in information for scientists studying the effects of forest management techniques. Fires have historically been common in California, where burning actually prompts many native plants and trees to release more seeds. Experts say many areas of California, where fires used to burn every 10 or 15 years, are now more vulnerable to catastrophic fire because the forests are overgrown. Story: http://sfg.ly/17eb24s

Staff Sgt. Ty Michael Carter, who grew up in Antioch, risked his life to save others in an Afghanistan battle. Afterward, he had trouble sleeping and blamed himself for the deaths of other soldiers. So he got help for post-traumatic stress disorder, and is helping others to work through it. Today he was awarded the Medal of Honor for both his battlefield heroics, and his PTSD work. "If you want to know what a true American hero looks like, then you don't have too look far," President Obama said to Carter's three children. "You just have to look at your dad."
Read more: http://sfg.ly/18X31EC

As a massive wildfire burning into Yosemite National Park grew to nearly 200 square miles, Gov. Jerry Brown declared a state of emergency for the city of San Francisco 150 miles away because of the threat to the city's utilities. The governor had already declared an emergency for the area around the fire but Friday night extended it to San Francisco, saying the blaze posed a threat to the city's power lines and stations in the fire area.

status_message:
Over the past decade, the number of African American men killed on the streets of Oakland nearly matched the number who graduated from its high schools ready to attend a state university. Against this backdrop, school officials became the first in the nation to create a department with the sole focus of helping African American males while sponsoring a charter school specifically for black boys. Over the past year, The Chronicle documented the fear, struggles and loss that African American males face in Oakland and the city's attempt to address them.

Read Part 1 of an important series by The Chronicle's Jill Tucker, with photos by Lacy Atkins: http://sfg.ly/1cXmWIc

Tomorrow night, Oakland A's star Yoenis Céspedes will be in the national spotlight as he competes in the All-Star Game Home Run Derby. Here is the astonishing story about his family that no one has learned, until now: 

Marooned on a tiny Caribbean island, Céspedes' family feared their journey would end right there under a baking sun. Their effort to follow Céspedes from Cuba to the United States had gone horribly wrong, leaving them abandoned for two days on a strip of sand more than 600 miles southeast of Florida.

The plane, Asiana Airlines Flight 214, crashed at 11:27 a.m. and came to rest on the side of runway 28L, one of four runways at SFO, said Lynn Lunsford, a spokeswoman with the Federal Aviation Administration. The plane appeared to make impact short of the runway - its tail was obliterated, leaving a trail of debris. 
Read the story: http://sfg.ly/16gJU51

Were you affected by the long BART delays today? An early morning crash between two maintenance vehicles in the Transbay Tube mangled 280 feet of the electric third rail on the track used by eastbound trains, BART said, reducing  service to a single track and causing long delays that forced tens of thousands of people to find other ways to get to and from San Francisco. When a gunman took her hostage in her pickup, Mill Valley contractor Tina Humphrey calmly showed him pictures of her kids, and asked a passer-by to get help. The troubled suspect was captured, and no one was hurt. "It's obvious her calm demeanor de-escalated the situation," Marin police said. "It was incredibly brave of her." The conspiracy-spouting suspect had a pistol in his pants pocket, and an AK-47 in his car.

So long, Sutro Sam! We hope you find love and happiness. The celebrated river otter that established his bachelor pad in a spring-fed pool at the ruins of Sutro Baths apparently had his fill of discarded pet goldfish and lit out, possibly in search of more sultry companionship, otter experts said Friday. The otter, dubbed Sutro Sam, was the first of the furry mammals seen in San Francisco in at least a half century, but he has not been seen along the rocky shore since Feb. 23. On October 13, 1966 salvage crews were hauling the U.S.S Johnson to a San Pedro scrap heap when the tow cable snapped and the 300-foot destroyer escort made  a "gentle landing" at Mori's Point Beach near Sharp Park.
